    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>What are the 5 love languages?</summary>
        <p>The 5 love languages are Words of Affirmation (verbal expressions of love and appreciation), Acts of Service (doing helpful things for someone), Receiving Gifts (thoughtful, tangible symbols of love), Quality Time (focused, undivided attention), and Physical Touch (physical closeness and affection). Developed by Dr. Gary Chapman, this framework describes the five primary ways people express and experience love. <a href="/test/love-language-test/">Take our free Love Language Test</a> to discover your primary language.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Can you have more than one love language?</summary>
        <p>Yes, most people resonate with more than one love language, though they typically have one or two that are dominant. You might strongly value both Quality Time and Physical Touch while Words of Affirmation matter less to you. The framework is designed to help you understand your primary preferences, not to box you into a single category. Knowing your top two languages gives you and your partner the most useful information for improving your relationship.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Do love languages change over time?</summary>
        <p>Love languages can shift over time based on life circumstances, personal growth, and relationship stage. A new parent might suddenly value Acts of Service more than ever because they are overwhelmed. Someone going through a difficult period might crave Words of Affirmation for reassurance. Major life events, stress levels, and changing priorities can all influence which language feels most important at any given time. It is worth revisiting your love language periodically.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What if my partner has a different love language?</summary>
        <p>Having different love languages is extremely common and does not indicate incompatibility. It simply means you need to learn to express love in your partner's preferred language, even if it does not come naturally. Share your own needs openly, ask your partner about theirs, and make a conscious effort to speak their language regularly. Think of it as becoming bilingual in love rather than facing a fundamental mismatch. The effort itself is an act of love.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Can love languages apply to non-romantic relationships?</summary>
        <p>Absolutely. Love languages apply to friendships, parent-child relationships, sibling relationships, and even workplace dynamics. A friend whose love language is Quality Time feels most valued when you give them your undivided attention. A child whose love language is Physical Touch needs hugs and closeness to feel secure. Understanding love languages across all your relationships helps you connect more deeply with everyone in your life, not just romantic partners.</p>
      </details>
    </section>

